<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">Introduction</h2>

<p><span style="font-size: x-large;"><img src="https://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs188/sp21/assets/images/treasure_hunting_pacman.png" width="400" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" /> </span></p>
<center style="box-sizing: border-box; color: #212529; font-family: Lato; font-size: 15.2px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">Much truth is unseen.</center><center style="box-sizing: border-box; color: #212529; font-family: Lato; font-size: 15.2px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">How will Pacman become sure?</center><center style="box-sizing: border-box; color: #212529; font-family: Lato; font-size: 15.2px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">Bayes Net Inference</center>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">In this project, you will implement inference algorithms for Bayes Nets, specifically variable elimination and value-of-perfect-information computations. These inference algorithms will allow you to reason about the existence of invisible pellets and ghosts.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">This project includes an autograder for you to grade your answers on your machine. This can be run on all questions with the command:</p>
<pre style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 16px; white-space: pre-wrap; word-wrap: break-word; line-height: 1.4em; margin: 1em 0px; color: #3c3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">  python autograder.py </pre>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">It can be run for one particular question, such as q2, by:</p>
<pre style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 16px; white-space: pre-wrap; word-wrap: break-word; line-height: 1.4em; margin: 1em 0px; color: #3c3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">  python autograder.py -q q2 </pre>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">It can be run for one particular test by commands of the form:</p>
<pre style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 16px; white-space: pre-wrap; word-wrap: break-word; line-height: 1.4em; margin: 1em 0px; color: #3c3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">  python autograder.py -t test_cases/q2/1-simple-eliminate </pre>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">See the autograder tutorial in Project 1 for more information about using the autograder.</p>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">TREASURE-HUNTING PACMAN</h2>

<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">Pacman has entered a world of mystery. Initially, the entire map is invisible. As he explores it, he learns information about neighboring cells. The map contains two houses: a ghost house, which is probably mostly red, and a food house, which is probably mostly blue. Pacman's goal is to enter the food house while avoiding the ghost house.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">Pacman will reason about which house is which based on his observations, and reason about the tradeoff between taking a chance or gathering more evidence. To enable this, you'll implement probabilistic inference using Bayes nets.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;">To play for yourself, run:</p>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">Bayes' Nets and Factors</h2>

<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">First, take a look at<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">bayesNet.py</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>to see the classes you'll be working with -<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">BayesNet</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>and<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">Factor</code>. You can also run this file to see an example<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">BayesNet</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>and associated<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">Factor</code>s:</p>
<pre style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 16px; white-space: pre-wrap; word-wrap: break-word; line-height: 1.4em; margin: 1em 0px; color: #3c3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">   python bayesNet.py </pre>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">You should look at the<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">printStarterBayesNet</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>function - there are helpful comments that can make your life<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><em style="line-height: 1.4em; font-style: italic;">much</em><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>easier later on.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">The Bayes' Net created in this function is shown below:</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="265" height="155" /></p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">A summary of the terminology is given below:</p>
<ul style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; list-style-position: outside; list-style-image: none; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">Bayes' Net: This is a representation of a probabilistic model as a directed acyclic graph and a set of conditional probability tables, one for each variable, as shown in lecture. The Traffic Bayes' Net above is an example.</li>
<li><span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">Factor: This stores a table of probabilities, although the sum of the entries in the table is not necessarily 1. <span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">A factor is of the general form $ P(X_1, \cdots, X_m, y_1, \cdots, y_n|Z_1, \cdots, Z_p, w_1, \cdots, w_q)$  <span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">Recall that lower case variables have already been assigned. For each possible assignment of values to the<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span></span>$ X_i$  and $ Z_j$  <span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">variables, the factor stores a single number. The $ Z_j$ , $ w_k$  <span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">variables are said to be conditioned while the $ X_i, y_l$  <span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">variables are unconditioned.</span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  display: inline !important; float: none;">Conditional Probability Table (CPT): This is a factor satisfying two properties:</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;"><span style="font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;">     1. Its entries must sum to 1 <span style="font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;">for each assignment of the conditional variables</span></span></span></p>
<p style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;"><span style="font-size: medium;">      2. There is exactly one unconditioned variable.</span></p>
<p><span style="color: #3c3c3c; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;"><span style="font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;"><span style="font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal;"><br class="Apple-interchange-newline" />   The Traffic Bayes' Net stores the following CPTs:</span></span></span></p>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">QUESTION 1 (3 POINTS): BAYES NET STRUCTURE</h2>

<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 25.6px; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">Implement the <code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">constructBayesNet</code> function in <code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">bayesAgents.py</code>. It constructs an empty Bayes net with the structure described below. (We'll specify the actual factors in the next question.)</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 25.6px; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">The treasure hunting world is generated according to the following Bayes net:</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width=60% /> <br class="Apple-interchange-newline" /> </p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 25.6px; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">Don't worry if this looks complicated! We'll take it step by step. As described in the code for<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">constructBayesNet</code>, we build the empty structure by listing all of the variables, their values, and the edges between them. This figure shows the variables and the edges, but what about their values?</p>
<ul style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; list-style: disc outside none; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;"><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">X positions</strong> determines which house goes on which side of the board. It is either <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">food-left</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>or <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">ghost-left</strong>.</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;"><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">Y positions</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>determines how the houses are vertically oriented. It models the vertical positions of both houses simultaneously, and has one of four values: <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">both-top</strong>,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><b style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">both-bottom</b>,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><b style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">left-top</b>, and <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">left-bottom</strong>. "left-top" is as the name suggests: the house on the left side of the board is on top, and the house on the right side of the board is on the bottom.</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;"><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">Food house</strong> and<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">ghost house</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>specify the actual positions of the two houses. They are both deterministic functions of "X positions" and "Y positions"</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">The <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">observations</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>are measurements that Pacman makes while traveling around the board. Note that there are many of these nodes---one for every board position that might be the wall of a house. If there is no house in a given location, the corresponding observation is<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><b style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">none</b>; otherwise it is either <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">red</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>or <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">blue</strong>, with the precise distribution of colors depending on the kind of house. </li>
</ul>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">QUESTION 2 (3 POINTS): BAYES NET PROBABILITIES</h2>

(We've already filled in the <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">X position</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>and <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">house</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>factors for you.)</p>

<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 25.6px; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  text-rendering: optimizeLegibility; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; font-stretch: inherit; vertical-align: baseline;">For an example of how to construct factors, look at the implementation of the factor for<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">X positions</strong>in <code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">fillXCPT</code>.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">The<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">Y positions</strong> are given by values<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">BOTH_TOP</code>,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">BOTH_BOTTOM</code>,<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">LEFT_TOP</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>and<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">LEFT_BOTTOM</code>. These variables, and their associated probabilities, are provided by constants at the top of the file.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">If you're interested, you can look at the computation for <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">house positions</strong>. All you need to remember is that each house can be in one of four positions: <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">top-left</strong>,<strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;"><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>top-right</strong>,<strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;"><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>bottom-left</strong>,<strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;"> </strong>or <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">bottom-right</strong>.</p>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; "><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">Observations</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>are more interesting. Every possible observation position is adjacent to a possible center for a house. Pacman might observe that position to contain a <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">red </strong>wall, a <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">blue</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>wall, or <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">no wall</strong>. These outcomes occur with the following probabilities (again defined in terms of constants at the top of the file):</p>
<ul style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 1em; line-height: 22.4px; color: #3c3c3c; list-style: disc outside none; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;  text-rendering: optimizeLegibility; border: 0px; outline: 0px; font-stretch: inherit; font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline;">
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">If the adjacent house center is occupied by neither the ghost house or the food house, an observation is <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">none</strong><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>with certainty (probability 1).</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">If the adjacent house center is occupied by the <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">ghost house</strong>, it is red with probability PROB_GHOST_RED and blue otherwise.</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">If the adjacent house center is occupied by the <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">food house</strong>, it is red with probability PROB_FOOD_RED and blue otherwise.</li>
</ul>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 20px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">IMPORTANT NOTE: the structure of the Bayes Net means that the food house and ghost house might be assigned to the same position. This will never occur in practice. But the observation CPT needs to be a proper distribution for every possible set of parents. In this case, you should use the <strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">food house distribution</strong>.</p>
<h4 style="color: #3c3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: 600; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4em; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; margin: 0px 0px 10px; text-align: left; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">Hints</h4>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">There are only four entries in the Y position factor, so you can specify each of those by hand. You'll have to be cleverer for the observation variables. You'll find it easiest to first loop over possible house positions, then over possible walls for each house, and finally over assignments to (wall color, ghost house position, food house position) triples. Remember to create a separate factor for <em style="line-height: 1.4em; font-style: italic;">every one</em><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>of the 4*7=28 possible observation positions.</p>

<pre style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 16px; white-space: pre-wrap; word-wrap: break-word; line-height: 1.4em; margin: 1em 0px; color: #3c3c3c; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">python autograder.py -t test_cases/q6/1-disconnected-eliminate</pre>
<p style="color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0px 0px 1.41575em; text-align: left; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6em !important; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; "><em style="line-height: 1.4em; font-style: italic;"><strong style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em;">Hints and Observations</strong></em></p>
<ul style="margin: 1em 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; list-style: disc outside none; font-family: 'Open Sans', Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; ">
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">The algorithm should iterate over hidden variables in elimination order, performing joining over and eliminating that variable, until the only the query and evidence variables remain.</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">The sum of the probabilities in your output factor should sum to one (so that it is a true conditional probability, conditioned on the evidence).</li>
<li style="line-height: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0.70788em;">Look at the<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">inferenceByEnumeration</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>function in<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span><code style="font-family: monospace, serif; font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em; color: #3c3c3c; background: none; padding: 0px;">inference.py</code><span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span>for an example on how to use the desired functions. (Reminder: Inference by enumeration first joins over all the variables and then eliminates all the hidden variables. In contrast, variable elimination interleaves join and eliminate by iterating over all the hidden variables and perform a join and eliminate on a single hidden variable before moving on to the next hidden variable.)</li>
</ul>
